## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **🚀 Quick Revision Checklist for KTU Exam:**

### TCP Client-Server Essentials
- ✅ TCP is **connection-oriented**, **reliable**, **byte-stream** based (SOCK_STREAM).
- ✅ Server call sequence: **`socket() → bind() → listen() → accept() → recv()/send() → close()`**.
- ✅ Client call sequence: **`socket() → connect() → send()/recv() → close()`**.
- ✅ Port number is **16-bit** (0–65535); always use `htons()` for **Network Byte Order**.
- ✅ `INADDR_ANY` binds server to **all available network interfaces**.
- ✅ 3-Way Handshake: **`SYN → SYN-ACK → ACK`** (3 packets before data).
- ✅ Connection termination is a **4-way handshake**: `FIN → ACK → FIN → ACK`.
- ✅ `accept()` returns a **NEW** socket descriptor; the original `server_fd` remains in `LISTEN` state.

### Matrix Classification Essentials
- ✅ Only **square matrices** qualify for these classifications.
- ✅ **Priority order:** `Diagonal → Upper → Lower → None`.
- ✅ **Upper Triangular:** zeros **below** diagonal ($i > j$).
- ✅ **Lower Triangular:** zeros **above** diagonal ($i < j$).
- ✅ **Diagonal:** all **off-diagonal** elements are zero ($i \neq j$).
- ✅ Loop indices (0-based): 
   - Upper: `i` from `1 to n-1`, `j` from `0 to i-1`
   - Lower: `i` from `0 to n-2`, `j` from `i+1 to n-1`
   - Diagonal: `i` from `0 to n-1`, `j` from `0 to n-1`, skip `i==j`
- ✅ Use **boolean flags** (`isUpper`, `isLower`, `isDiagonal`) initialized to `1`, set to `0` on first violation.
- ✅ **Optimization tip:** Combine all three checks in a single nested loop for efficiency.

### Common Viva Questions
- 🎤 *"What happens if you don't call `bind()` on the server?"* → The OS auto-assigns a random port (`Ephemeral Port`). The client won't know which port to connect to.
- 🎤 *"What's the difference between `close()` and `shutdown()`?"* → `close()` decrements reference count; `shutdown()` forces immediate termination of read/write half.
- 🎤 *"Why is TCP called a byte-stream protocol?"* → It treats data as a continuous stream of bytes with no inherent message boundaries.
- 🎤 *"What does `htons` stand for?"* → **H**ost **TO** **N**etwork **S**hort (16-bit conversion).
- 🎤 *"Can a $1 \times 1$ matrix be diagonal?"* → Yes! A single-element matrix has no off-diagonal elements, so it trivially satisfies all three conditions; per KTU convention, label it **DIAGONAL**.

> [!TIP]
> **Final Exam Tip:** KTU often includes a **trace question** asking you to show the output for a sample matrix. Practice running the program mentally with matrices like `[[5,0,0],[0,3,0],[0,0,7]]` (Diagonal), `[[1,2,3],[0,4,5],[0,0,6]]` (Upper), and `[[1,0,0],[2,3,0],[4,5,6]]` (Lower) before the exam.
