## SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

A **Concurrent File Server** is a network application architecture that uses the **TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)** to listen for client connections on a designated port and spawns a *separate child process* (or thread) to handle each incoming client request independently, without blocking the main listening process. In the specific variation known as **"Concurrent File Server with PID Response,"** the server, upon accepting a client connection, identifies itself by transmitting its own **Process Identifier (PID)** — a unique positive integer assigned by the operating system kernel to every running process — back to the requesting client, typically followed by a file read/write operation.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight (PCCSL507):**
> This experiment belongs to **Module 2 – Socket Programming** and directly tests the following Course Outcomes:
> - **CO2:** Implement client-server programs using TCP and UDP sockets.
> - **CO3:** Apply process/thread management primitives to build concurrent network services.
> **Bloom's Level:** *Apply (L3)* and *Analyse (L4)*.

---

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — "The Bank Teller Counter"

Imagine a busy bank branch:
- The **main door / reception desk** = the **listening socket** of the server. It constantly watches for new customers walking in.
- The **bank manager at the door** = the **parent server process**. The manager does *not* serve customers personally. Instead, every time a new customer arrives, the manager shouts, *"Hey! Start a new teller window for this customer!"* — this is the **`fork()`** system call.
- The **newly opened teller window with a unique name tag** = the **child process** with a unique **PID**. The name tag (PID) is shown to the customer so the manager can later look up which window is handling which request.
- The **customer** = the **client process** connected over a TCP socket.

> [!NOTE]
> **Why send the PID?**
> In a concurrent system, multiple identical child processes are running simultaneously. Returning the **PID** allows the client to:
> 1. Verify that the server actually *forked* a dedicated process for it.
> 2. Log which server-side process handled its request — useful for **debugging, auditing, and process tracking**.
> 3. Understand the **1-to-1 process-to-client mapping** central to the concurrent server model.

### 1.3 Key Terminology Box

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| **PID (Process Identifier)** | A unique non-negative integer (typically **≤ 32768** on 32-bit Linux) assigned by the kernel to identify a process. PID **1** is reserved for `init/systemd`. |
| **Concurrent Server** | A server that handles **multiple clients simultaneously** using `fork()`, `pthread_create()`, or non-blocking I/O. |
| **Iterative Server** | A server that handles **one client at a time**; subsequent clients wait in the kernel's accept queue. |
| **socket()** | The POSIX system call that creates an endpoint for communication, returning a file descriptor. |
| **bind()** | Associates a socket with a specific **IP address** and **port number**. |
| **listen()** | Marks the socket as passive, ready to accept incoming connection requests. |
| **accept()** | Blocks until a client connection arrives, returning a **new socket file descriptor** for communication. |
| **fork()** | Creates a child process that is an almost-identical copy of the parent. Returns **0** to child, **child PID** to parent. |
| **Port Number** | A 16-bit unsigned integer (**0–65535**). Well-known ports: **0–1023**; Registered: **1024–49151**; Dynamic: **49152–65535**. |

