## SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Code Analysis & Analytical Matrix

> [!NOTE]
> Since this is the **Networks Lab (PCCSL507)** — a CS programming course — **code is mandated by the experiment**. Full, compilable implementations for both client and server are provided below with exhaustive step-by-step logic. The language used is **C** (the KTU 2024 prescribed lab language for socket programming).

### 3.1 Server Program — `concurrent_server.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/socket.h>
#include <netinet/in.h>
#include <arpa/inet.h>

#define PORT 8080
#define BUF_SIZE 1024

int main() {
    int sockfd, newsockfd;
    socklen_t clilen;
    char buffer[BUF_SIZE];
    struct sockaddr_in serv_addr, cli_addr;
    int n;

    // ---------------- STEP 1: Create the listening socket ----------------
    sockfd = socket(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, 0);
    if (sockfd < 0) {
        perror("ERROR opening socket");
        exit(1);
    }

    // ---------------- STEP 2: Zero the server address structure ----------
    bzero((char *) &serv_addr, sizeof(serv_addr));
    serv_addr.sin_family      = AF_INET;
    serv_addr.sin_addr.s_addr = INADDR_ANY;      // accept on any interface
    serv_addr.sin_port        = htons(PORT);     // host → network byte order

    // ---------------- STEP 3: Bind the socket to the address ------------
    if (bind(sockfd, (struct sockaddr *) &serv_addr, sizeof(serv_addr)) < 0) {
        perror("ERROR on binding");
        exit(1);
    }

    // ---------------- STEP 4: Listen for clients (backlog = 5) ----------
    listen(sockfd, 5);
    clilen = sizeof(cli_addr);

    printf("Concurrent File Server listening on port %d...\n", PORT);

    // ---------------- STEP 5: Infinite accept-loop, fork per client ------
    while (1) {
        newsockfd = accept(sockfd, (struct sockaddr *) &cli_addr, &clilen);
        if (newsockfd < 0) {
            perror("ERROR on accept");
            continue;
        }

        pid_t pid = fork();          // create child process
        if (pid < 0) {
            perror("ERROR on fork");
            exit(1);
        }

        if (pid == 0) {
            // --------------- CHILD PROCESS ---------------
            close(sockfd);           // child does not need the listener

            pid_t mypid = getpid();                          // get this child's PID
            char pid_str[32];
            sprintf(pid_str, "PID:%d\n", mypid);             // format PID as string

            // Send PID to client
            n = write(newsockfd, pid_str, strlen(pid_str));
            if (n < 0) perror("ERROR writing PID");

            // Optional: receive filename from client and transmit file
            bzero(buffer, BUF_SIZE);
            n = read(newsockfd, buffer, BUF_SIZE - 1);
            if (n > 0) {
                buffer[n] = '\0';
                printf("Child PID %d: client requested file '%s'\n", mypid, buffer);

                FILE *fp = fopen(buffer, "r");
                if (fp == NULL) {
                    char *err = "ERROR: file not found\n";
                    write(newsockfd, err, strlen(err));
                } else {
                    while (fgets(buffer, BUF_SIZE, fp) != NULL) {
                        write(newsockfd, buffer, strlen(buffer));
                    }
                    fclose(fp);
                }
            }

            close(newsockfd);        // child done
            exit(0);                 // terminate child cleanly
        }
        else {
            // --------------- PARENT PROCESS ---------------
            close(newsockfd);        // parent does not need the connected socket
            // parent loops back to accept() immediately
        }
    }

    close(sockfd);
    return 0;
}
```

---

### 3.2 Line-by-Line Analytical Matrix

| Line | Construct | Why It Is Here (Conversion Logic) |
|---|---|---|
| `socket(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, 0)` | Creates TCP socket | `AF_INET` = IPv4, `SOCK_STREAM` = TCP (connection-oriented, reliable byte stream). |
| `bzero(&serv_addr, sizeof(...))` | Zero-initialise struct | Prevents garbage values in unused fields (good C hygiene). |
| `serv_addr.sin_family = AF_INET` | Set address family | Tells kernel we are using IPv4. |
| `serv_addr.sin_addr.s_addr = INADDR_ANY` | Listen on 0.0.0.0 | Server accepts connections arriving on *any* of its IPs (Wi-Fi, Ethernet, loopback). |
| `serv_addr.sin_port = htons(PORT)` | Port conversion | x86 CPUs are **little-endian**; network is **big-endian**. `htons` = host-to-network short. |
| `bind(sockfd, ...)` | Bind to IP+port | Associates the abstract socket with a concrete (IP, port) tuple. |
| `listen(sockfd, 5)` | Mark as passive | The integer `5` is the **maximum length of the pending-connection queue** before the kernel refuses new SYNs. |
| `accept(sockfd, ...)` | Block for client | Awaits a completed 3-way TCP handshake; on success, returns a *new* fd. |
| `fork()` | Duplicate process | After fork, *both* processes have the same `sockfd` and `newsockfd` integers. We split duties. |
| `if (pid == 0)` | Child branch | Child must close `sockfd` (its copy of the listener) to avoid file-descriptor leaks; the OS keeps the listener alive because the parent still has it. |
| `getpid()` | Get child PID | Returns the kernel-assigned PID of *this* process — sent to client as proof of concurrency. |
| `sprintf(pid_str, ...)` | PID → string | Network sockets carry bytes; integers must be converted. |
| `write(newsockfd, pid_str, ...)` | Send PID | TCP guarantees ordered, reliable delivery. |
| `read(newsockfd, buffer, ...)` | Receive filename | Blocks until data arrives from client. |
| `fopen(buffer, "r")` | Open requested file | The "file server" functionality — serves file contents. |
| `close(newsockfd); exit(0);` | Cleanup | Closes socket and terminates child, returning resources to OS. |
| `close(newsockfd)` (parent) | Release socket ref | Parent must close its copy; otherwise the socket cannot be fully reclaimed even after the child exits. |

