### ✅ **Question A (14 Marks)**

#### **Q.A.(a) [7 Marks] — [KTU University Exam – May 2024]**
**Explain the `socket()`, `bind()`, `listen()`, `accept()`, and `connect()` system calls used in TCP client-server programming. Mention the headers required.**

**Model Answer (7 marks):**

1. **`socket(int domain, int type, int protocol)`** — Creates an endpoint for communication. Returns a file descriptor (non-negative on success, -1 on error). For IPv4 TCP we use `AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, 0`. *(1.5 marks)*
2. **`bind(int sockfd, struct sockaddr *addr, socklen_t addrlen)`** — Binds the socket to a specific IP address and port number. Returns 0 on success. Used only on the **server** side. *(1.5 marks)*
3. **`listen(int sockfd, int backlog)`** — Converts the socket into a *passive* socket, ready to accept incoming connections. `backlog` defines the maximum length of the queue of pending connections. Used only on the **server** side. *(1.5 marks)*
4. **`accept(int sockfd, struct sockaddr *addr, socklen_t *addrlen)`** — Blocks until a client connects; on success returns a **new** file descriptor for the established connection. The original `sockfd` continues to listen. *(1.5 marks)*
5. **`connect(int sockfd, struct sockaddr *addr, socklen_t addrlen)`** — Initiates a TCP three-way handshake (SYN → SYN-ACK → ACK) with the server. Used on the **client** side. Returns 0 on success. *(1 mark)*

**Required headers:**
```c
#include <sys/socket.h>
#include <netinet/in.h>
#include <arpa/inet.h>
#include <unistd.h>
```

