### ✅ **Question B (14 Marks) — Alternative Choice**

#### **Q.B.(a) [7 Marks] — [KTU University Exam – May 2024]**
**Describe the working of the `fork()` system call. What are the return values in the parent and child? Why is `close()` called twice (once in parent, once in child) on different file descriptors after `fork()`?**

**Model Answer (7 marks):**
- `fork()` is a POSIX system call that creates a new process by duplicating the calling process. The new process (child) is an almost-identical copy of the original (parent). *(1 mark)*
- **Return values:** *(2 marks)*
  - In the **parent**: returns the **PID of the newly created child** (a positive integer).
  - In the **child**: returns **0**.
  - On error: returns **-1** in the parent (no child is created).
- The child has its own copy of the parent's **file descriptor table**, so both processes share open references to the same kernel socket objects. *(1 mark)*
- **Why `close()` is called twice:** *(3 marks)*
  - In the **child**, `close(sockfd)` is called on the **listening socket** because the child does not need to accept new connections — its only job is to service the current client via `newsockfd`.
  - In the **parent**, `close(newsockfd)` is called on the **connected socket** because the parent has already handed it off to the child; keeping it open would prevent the kernel from cleaning up the socket even after the child exits.
  - This avoids **file-descriptor leaks** and the *"address already in use"* error when the server restarts.

